Values.value:
A unique and unambiguous label to help users understand and differentiate one CDE from another. No character limit.
Examples: Visit Date Head circumference measurement Chest X-ray result Usual Place of Health Care Type

If your CDE is NIH-Endorsed and in the NIH CDE Repository (https://cde.nlm.nih.gov/), enter the NLM identifier and and STOP here.
To reuse NIH-endorsed CDEs in the NIH CDE Repository, only CDE Name and NLM ID are needed.
If your CDE is in the Repository but not endorsed, enter the NLM ID, and continue filling out all required fields.
The NLM identifier is found on the CDE page > CDE Details > Identifiers.
Other identifiers for your CDEs, e.g., variable names created by your project or institute.

Select the type of data to be collected from the dropdown list: Value List, Text, Number, Date, Time, Datetime, Geolocation, File/URI/URL.
If your CDE does not fit any of the above data types, select Other and we will provide assistance.

A textual definition created by a Subject Matter Expert (SME) that describes the CDE in detail.
Example: “Date of interview or visit (the date when data in the form were captured)."
The preferred text to be used on a case report form, data collection template, questionnaire, or measure, to standardize how the data are collected
If CDE Data Type is "Number", you may provide the unit of measure for this value.

The source of the CDE may be an existing instrument, project, or other authoritative source. If it is a new CDE, enter your project name as the source.
NIH ICO names are not acceptable. Please be more specific.
If more than one Source is provided, use a pipe "|" to separate values in the list.
Example: Limb Loss Research Standards (NCMRR) Example: PhenX 10801 Current Address https://www.phenxtoolkit.org/protocols/view/ 10801

Data element concepts (DECs) others find your CDE and understand what your CDE is intended to capture or measure. DECs may be used to group similar CDEs in the Repository.
You can find DECs in a standard terminology or thesaurus, such as the NCI Thesaurus, the UMLS Metathesaurus, MeSH, etc. Search for DECs for each CDE, and paste the name and concept identifier(s) below.
If more than one DEC is used, separate values with a pipe "|".
For example, the UMLS identifier for Head Circumference is C0262499 (https://uts.nlm.nih.gov/uts/umls/concept/C0262499). You would enter Head Circumference C026249 A second example: the NCI Thesaurus identifier for the concept Age is C25150. You would enter Age C25150

Source of the Data Element Concept Identifier.
If more than one DEC is used, separate values with a pipe "|".
The number and order of Terminology Sources should correspond to the number and order of the DECs. If more than one DEC is provided, and the source is the same for all, repeat the source.
Example: UMLS|NCIt Example: NCIt|NCIt|NCIt

If the CDE is a Composite or part of a Bundled Set of Questions, select the appropriate label from the dropdown list. See Glossary for definitions of these terms.
Leave blank for individual CDEs.

If CDE is a Composite or part of a Bundled Set of Questions, enter the name of the composite or bundle.
Leave blank for individual CDEs.

If CDE Data Type is Value List, a list of permissible values is required.
Use a pipe "|" to separate values in the list. Example: yes|no|unknown
Or provide a reference URL/URI that points to the full list of permissible values.
Alternatively, you may provide an object identifier for a VSAC value set. See https://vsac.nlm.nih.gov/ for more information.

If CDE Data Type is Value List, a definition is required for each PV. In some cases, PV Definitions may be found in the same terminology system as the PV Concept Identifier.
Use a pipe "|" to separate Definitions in the list. The number and order of Definitions should correspond to the number and order of the PV Labels.

Identifier(s) for the terminology concept(s) associated with the PV Labels. One source for concept identifiers is the UMLS Metathesarus.
Use a pipe "|" to separate Concept Identifiers in the list. The number and order of Concept Identifiers should correspond to the number and order of the PV Labels.

The terminology system from which the Permissible Value Concept Identifier is drawn.
If you provide a PV Concept Identifier, you must provide a PV Terminology Source for the identifier. Use a pipe "|" to separate values in the list.
The number and order of Terminology Sources should correspond to the number and order of PV Concept Identifiers. Repeat the source for every identifier, even if the source is the same for all.
Example: UMLS|UMLS|UMLS|UMLS

A code representing the Permissible Value. For example, some information systems store codes for interoperability.
Example: for Permissible Value Labels Yes| No, the system might store Codes such as 1|0 or Y|N.
Or codes might come from a standard coding system such as LOINC or SNOMED CT; for example: LA26683-5|LA4489-6.
Use a pipe "|" to separate values in the list.
There must be the same number of PV Codes as there are PV Labels, and they should be listed in the same order.

The system from which the code is drawn.
If codes are locally generated, leave blank.
Please use a pipe "|" to separate values in the list.
The number and order of Code Systems should correspond to the number and order of Codes.

If there is published evidence on the validity/reliability in target populations of a bundle or CDE, provide the reference here, to validation publication(s). DOIs, PubMed IDs, or other unique stable identifiers are preferred. URLs (if available) are acceptable.
If your CDE is part of a standardized instrument, or is directly pulled from external guidance, provide at least one Reference.
If used for different populations, please include references for each.

Unstructured set of terms or phrases that describe what the CDE is about. Only include terms/phrases that are not already in the CDE metadata (as part of the name, definition, permissible values, etc.).
